[1
Date: 7 Jan 1999
From: "Robert A. LaBudde" <ral@lcfltd.com
Source: News Media
Michigan - Officials said on Wednesday that two more cattle herds in
northeast Lower Michigan are infected with bovine tuberculosis,
threatening the state's classification as free from bovine TB. Loss of
the TB-free designation could lead to a requirement that cattle be
tested for the chronic lung disease before shipping out of Michigan,
chilling the market for Michigan meat. Michigan officials said that it
will be two or three months before the federal government will act.
State Agriculture Director Dan Wyant was quoted as saying, "These
findings do not represent a food safety concern. It is a concern of the
marketability. While we are disappointed with these results, we remain
focused on our objective of eliminating bovine tuberculosis from both
livestock and wildlife in Michigan. We're continuing with our plan to
test cattle, goats and captive deer and elk in the five-county area of
northeast Michigan affected by TB."
__
Robert A. LaBudde
e-mail: ral@lcfltd.com
