[2
Date: Jan. 8, 1999
From:Ken Waldrup <kenw@ftworth.tahc.state.tx.us>
Subject: TB testing
[There was question that came in from one our readers inquiring about
the type of testing used on dead animals. I forwarded his question to
Dr. Waldrup who has had tremendous experience with this topic. Ken,
Thanks for your reply - Mod.TG
Testing of dead animals merely involves looking for gross lesions in
lymph nodes, histopathology and acid-fast stains of tissues and culture,
though culture can take up to 8 weeks. ELISA is a serologic test and
requires serum. We are doing similar "testing" of hunter-killed
whitetails in Texas right now. Some folks have tried using PCR on
tissues -- works sometimes, sometimes not. The standard procedure would
be to remove and visually examine the lymph nodes from the head (medial
retropharygeals, lateral retropharyngeals and parietals), thorax
(pulmonary and mediastinals) and abdomen (hepatics, abomasal,
mesenterics and ileocecal) plus whatever peripheral nodes you could get
(popliteal, mammary, prescapular). Section each node and look for an
obvious lesion. If a lesion is noted or for survey purposes, freeze
half the node and put the other half in formalin. Culture the frozen
tissue (_M. bovis_ survives freezing very well) and cut and stain the
fixed tissue. If one sees acid-fast bacteria in the tissue, the sample
is classified as "lesion compatible" and culture would have to sort out
whether it was _M. bovis, M. avium_ or one of at least a dozen other
saprophytic mycobacteria found in North America.
__
Ken Waldrup, DVM, PhD
Field Veterinarian, Area 3
Texas Animal Health Commisssion
kenw@ftworth.tahc.state.tx.us
